SENATE BILL 509
F2 6lr1457
By: Senator Rosapepe Senators Rosapepe, Attar, and Hester
Introduced and read first time: February 2, 2026
Assigned to: Education, Energy, and the Environment
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
Senate action: Adopted
Read second time: March 3, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Higher Education – Workforce Pell Grant Program – Implementation
3 FOR the purpose of implementing the federal Workforce Pell Grant Program in the State;
4 requiring the Governor, after consultation with certain entities, to determine
5 whether to approve certain short–term programs as eligible for Pell Grant funds
6 subject to certain requirements; requiring a certain registered apprenticeship
7 program to include certain components in the curriculum; prohibiting institutions of
8 postsecondary education from using certain funds subject to a certain exclusion;
9 prohibiting institutions of postsecondary education from operating short–term
10 programs in a certain manner; and generally relating to the Workforce Pell Grant
11 Program.
12 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
13 Article – Education
14 Section 10–101(a), (c), and (i)
15 Annotated Code of Maryland
16 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
17 BY adding to
18 Article – Education
19 Section 11–212
20 Annotated Code of Maryland
21 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *sb0509*

2 SENATE BILL 509
1 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
2 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
3 Article – Education
4 10–101.
5 (a) In this division the following words have the meanings indicated.
6 (c) “Commission” means the Maryland Higher Education Commission.
7 (i) (1) “Institution of postsecondary education” means a school or other
8 institution that offers an educational program in the State for individuals who are at least
9 16 years old and who have graduated from or left elementary or secondary school.
10 (2) “Institution of postsecondary education” does not include:
11 (i) Any adult education, evening high school, or high school
12 equivalence program conducted by a public school system of the State; or
13 (ii) Any apprenticeship or on–the–job training program subject to
14 approval by the Apprenticeship and Training Council.
15 11–212.
16 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
17 INDICATED.
18 (2) “PROGRAM” MEANS THE FEDERAL WORKFORCE PELL GRANT
19 PROGRAM BY WHICH PELL GRANTS MAY BE AWARDED TO STUDENTS ENROLLED IN
20 A SHORT–TERM PROGRAM IN ACCORDANCE WITH SECTION 83002 OF THE ONE BIG
21 BEAUTIFUL BILL ACT, AS AMENDED.
22 (3) “REGISTERED APPRENTICESHIP” MEANS AN APPRENTICESHIP
23 PROGRAM THAT IS REGISTERED WITH, AND APPROVED BY, THE U.S. DEPARTMENT
24 OF LABOR OR THE MARYLAND APPRENTICESHIP AND TRAINING COUNCIL.
25 (3) (4) “SHORT–TERM PROGRAM” MEANS A PROGRAM OF STUDY
26 THAT IS:
27 (I) AT LEAST 150 HOURS OF INSTRUCTION;
28 (II) LESS THAN 600 HOURS OF INSTRUCTION;
29 (III) AT LEAST 8 WEEKS;

SENATE BILL 509 3
1 (IV) LESS THAN 15 WEEKS; AND
2 (V) NOT A CORRESPONDENCE COURSE AS DEFINED IN TITLE
3 34, SUBTITLE B, CHAPTER VI, PART 600 OF THE CODE OF FEDERAL REGULATIONS
4 IN EFFECT ON JULY 1, 2021.
5 (B) THE PURPOSE OF THIS SECTION IS TO IMPLEMENT THE WORKFORCE
6 PELL GRANT PROGRAM IN THE STATE.
7 (C) (1) THE GOVERNOR, AFTER CONSULTING WITH THE GOVERNOR’S
8 WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT BOARD AND THE COMMISSION, SHALL DETERMINE
9 WHETHER:
10 (I) A A SHORT–TERM PROGRAM OFFERED AT AN INSTITUTION
11 OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION MEETS THE REQUIREMENTS OF THIS SECTION AND
12 FEDERAL LAW FOR WORKFORCE PELL GRANTS; AND
13 (II) TO APPROVE THE SHORT–TERM PROGRAM AS ELIGIBLE FOR
14 THE PROGRAM.
15 (2) (I) SUBJECT TO SUBPARAGRAPH (II) OF THIS PARAGRAPH, AN
16 INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION, REGARDLESS OF HAVING A
17 PHYSICAL PRESENCE IN THE STATE, MAY NOT:
18 1. DISBURSE PROGRAM FUNDS TO A STUDENT IN THE
19 STATE; OR
20 2. ADVERTISE, MARKET, OR INFORM STUDENTS IN THE
21 STATE ABOUT THE AVAILABILITY OF PROGRAM FUNDS FOR A SHORT–TERM
22 PROGRAM.
23 (II) SUBPARAGRAPH (I) OF THIS PARAGRAPH DOES NOT APPLY
24 IF AN INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION, REGARDLESS OF HAVING A
25 PHYSICAL PRESENCE IN THE STATE, OBTAINS:
26 1. THE APPROVAL OF THE GOVERNOR UNDER THIS
27 SECTION FOR EACH SHORT–TERM PROGRAM FOR WHICH THE INSTITUTION OF
28 POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION SEEKS TO DISBURSE PROGRAM FUNDS; AND
29 2. A DETERMINATION FROM THE SECRETARY OF THE
30 U.S. DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION THAT THE INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY
31 EDUCATION MEETS THE REQUIREMENTS OF THE PROGRAM FOR EACH SHORT–TERM

4 SENATE BILL 509
1 PROGRAM FOR WHICH THE INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION SEEKS TO
2 DISBURSE PROGRAM FUNDS.
3 (3) FOR THE APPROVAL TO REMAIN EFFECTIVE, EVERY 2 YEARS AN
4 INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION SHALL PROVIDE INFORMATION
5 VERIFYING THE SHORT–TERM PROGRAM REMAINS IN COMPLIANCE WITH THIS
6 SECTION AND THE PROGRAM.
7 (4) IF THE ATTORNEY GENERAL OR COURT OF APPROPRIATE
8 JURISDICTION FINDS THE INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION ENGAGED
9 IN UNFAIR, DECEPTIVE, OR ABUSIVE TRADE PRACTICE UNDER TITLE 13 OF THE
10 COMMERCIAL LAW ARTICLE RELATED TO THE PROGRAM, THE GOVERNOR SHALL
11 REVOKE AN APPROVAL.
12 (D) (1) SUBJECT TO PARAGRAPH (2) OF THIS SUBSECTION, A
13 SHORT–TERM PROGRAM SEEKING APPROVAL UNDER THIS SECTION SHALL:
14 (I) PROVIDE AN EDUCATION ALIGNED WITH THE
15 REQUIREMENTS OF:
16 1. A HIGH–SKILL, HIGH–SKILL OR HIGH–WAGE
17 OCCUPATION AS IDENTIFIED BY THE STATE UNDER THE CARL D. PERKINS CAREER
18 AND TECHNICAL EDUCATION ACT; OR
19 2. AN IN–DEMAND INDUSTRY SECTOR OR OCCUPATION;
20 (II) MEET THE HIRING REQUIREMENTS OF EMPLOYERS IN THE
21 SECTORS OR OCCUPATIONS IDENTIFIED UNDER ITEM (I) OF THIS PARAGRAPH;
22 (III) 1. LEAD TO A RECOGNIZED POSTSECONDARY
23 CREDENTIAL THAT IS STACKABLE AND PORTABLE ACROSS MORE THAN ONE
24 EMPLOYER; OR
25 2. PREPARE STUDENTS ENROLLED IN THE SHORT–TERM
26 PROGRAM FOR EMPLOYMENT IN AN OCCUPATION FOR WHICH THERE IS ONLY ONE
27 RECOGNIZED POSTSECONDARY CREDENTIAL AND THAT AWARDS STUDENTS WITH
28 THE CREDENTIAL ON COMPLETION OF THE SHORT–TERM PROGRAM; AND
29 (IV) PREPARE STUDENTS TO PURSUE ONE OR MORE
30 CERTIFICATES OR DEGREES AT AN INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION
31 BY ENSURING THAT:

SENATE BILL 509 5
1 1. ON COMPLETION OF THE SHORT–TERM PROGRAM
2 AND ENROLLMENT IN A RELATED CERTIFICATE OR DEGREE PROGRAM, A STUDENT
3 WILL RECEIVE ACADEMIC CREDIT THAT AN INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY
4 EDUCATION WILL ACCEPT TOWARD THAT CERTIFICATE OR DEGREE; AND
5 2. THE ACADEMIC CREDIT DESCRIBED UNDER ITEM 1 OF
6 THIS ITEM WILL BE ACCEPTED TOWARD MEETING THE CERTIFICATE OR DEGREE
7 PROGRAM REQUIREMENTS.
8 (2) THERE IS A REBUTTABLE PRESUMPTION THAT THE THE RELATED
9 TECHNICAL INSTRUCTION COMPONENT OF A FEDERALLY REGISTERED OR
10 STATE–REGISTERED REGISTERED APPRENTICESHIP PROGRAM OFFERED AT AN
11 INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION SATISFIES THE REQUIREMENTS OF
12 PARAGRAPH PARAGRAPHS (1)(I), (II), AND (III) AND (3)(III) OF THIS SUBSECTION.
13 (3) IN ADDITION TO THE REQUIREMENTS OF PARAGRAPHS (1) AND (2)
14 OF THIS SUBSECTION, AN INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION SEEKING
15 APPROVAL UNDER THIS SECTION SHALL PROVIDE:
16 (I) DOCUMENTATION THAT, FOR THE 12 MONTHS PRECEDING
17 THE DATE ON WHICH THE INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION APPLIED
18 FOR APPROVAL, THE INSTITUTION OFFERED THE SHORT–TERM PROGRAM AND THE
19 SHORT–TERM PROGRAM MET ALL REQUIREMENTS OF THIS SECTION;
20 (II) DOCUMENTATION THAT THE SHORT–TERM PROGRAM HAS A
21 COMPLETION RATE OF AT LEAST 70% WITHIN 150% OF THE NORMAL TIME FOR
22 COMPLETION FOR EACH FEDERAL AID AWARD YEAR;
23 (III) DOCUMENTATION THAT THE SHORT–TERM PROGRAM HAS A
24 JOB PLACEMENT RATE OF AT LEAST 70% AFTER 180 DAYS OF COMPLETION FOR
25 EACH FEDERAL AID AWARD YEAR;
26 (IV) DOCUMENTATION THAT THE TUITION AND FEES FOR THE
27 SHORT–TERM PROGRAM ARE IN COMPLIANCE WITH THE REQUIREMENTS OF THE
28 PROGRAM; AND
29 (V) ANY INFORMATION THE GOVERNOR’S WORKFORCE
30 DEVELOPMENT BOARD OR THE COMMISSION REQUESTS TO VERIFY COMPLIANCE
31 WITH THIS SECTION AND THE PROGRAM.
32 (4) THE GOVERNOR’S WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT BOARD, THE
33 COMMISSION, OR ANY OTHER AUTHORIZED ENTITY MAY COLLECT AN APPLICATION
34 FEE TO COMPLETE THE EVALUATION.

6 SENATE BILL 509
1 (E) A REGISTERED APPRENTICESHIP PROGRAM APPROVED FOR
2 WORKFORCE PELL GRANTS SHALL INCLUDE IN THE CURRICULUM BOTH
3 ON–THE–JOB LEARNING AND CLASSROOM LEARNING, INCLUDING ARTIFACTS AND
4 DEMONSTRATED PERFORMANCE OR COMPETENCY ASSESSMENT, UNDER THE
5 GENERAL SUPERVISION OF THE FACULTY.
6 (E) (F) IN THE OPERATION OF A SHORT–TERM PROGRAM THAT IS
7 AUTHORIZED UNDER THIS SECTION, AN INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY
8 EDUCATION MAY NOT:
9 (1) PARTNER, CONTRACT, OR AFFILIATE WITH AN ENTITY,
10 INSTITUTION, OR ORGANIZATION OTHER THAN A JOINT APPRENTICESHIP
11 COMMITTEE REGISTERED APPRENTICESHIP, TO OFFER INSTRUCTION FOR THE
12 SHORT–TERM PROGRAM THAT IS NOT ACCREDITED BY AN ACCREDITING AGENCY
13 RECOGNIZED AND APPROVED BY THE U.S. DEPARTMENT OF EDUCATION; UNLESS
14 THE CONTRACTING ENTITY, INSTITUTION, OR ORGANIZATION:
15 (I) CLEARLY AND PROMINENTLY DISCLOSES THAT THE
16 CONTRACTING ENTITY IS A COMPANY THAT IS SEPARATE FROM THE INSTITUTION OF
17 POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION AND DESCRIBES ALL OF THE SERVICES THAT THE
18 CONTRACTING ENTITY IS CONTRACTED TO PROVIDE FOR THE INSTITUTION IN THE
19 FOLLOWING PLACES:
20 1. ON THE INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY
21 EDUCATION’S WEBSITE;
22 2. IN MARKETING MATERIALS ABOUT THE SHORT–TERM
23 PROGRAM; AND
24 3. IN ORAL COMMUNICATIONS WITH PROSPECTIVE
25 STUDENTS OF THE SHORT–TERM PROGRAM;
26 (II) IS NOT PAID USING INCENTIVE COMPENSATION OR TUITION
27 SHARING WITH THE INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION; AND
28 (III) IS NOT INVOLVED WITH THE INSTITUTION OF
29 POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION’S GOVERNANCE, DECISION MAKING OVER THE
30 DESIGN OR DEVELOPMENT OF COURSE CURRICULUM OR INSTRUCTION, SETTING OF
31 SHORT–TERM PROGRAM ADMISSION STANDARDS, DETERMINING ENROLLMENT
32 TARGETS, OR CREATION OF NEW SHORT–TERM PROGRAMS;

SENATE BILL 509 7
1 (2) UNLESS A LOAN IS 0% INTEREST, PARTNER OR AFFILIATE WITH
2 AN ENTITY THAT OFFERS STUDENT LOANS, LINES OF CREDIT, OR INCOME SHARING
3 AGREEMENTS FOR THE SHORT–TERM PROGRAM;
4 (3) CHARGE TUITION AND FEES TO ANY STUDENT ENROLLED IN THE
5 SHORT–TERM PROGRAM THAT ARE GREATER THAN THE MAXIMUM AMOUNT OF PELL
6 GRANT FUNDS AVAILABLE FOR ANY STUDENT IN THAT SHORT–TERM PROGRAM, AS
7 ESTABLISHED BY THE SECRETARY OF EDUCATION, FOR THE PERIOD OF TIME THAT
8 THE SHORT–TERM PROGRAM IS OFFERED; OR
9 (4) OFFER THE SHORT–TERM PROGRAM USING
10 NON–CREDIT–BEARING COURSES UNLESS THOSE COURSES WILL TRANSFER TO AT
11 LEAST ONE INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION REGARDLESS OF
12 PROGRAM COMPLETION.
13 (F) (1) ON OR BEFORE JUNE 30 EACH YEAR, FOR EACH SHORT–TERM
14 PROGRAM APPROVED UNDER THIS SECTION, THE INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY
15 EDUCATION SHALL REPORT TO THE COMMISSION ON:
16 (I) THE NUMBER OF STUDENTS ENROLLED IN SHORT–TERM
17 PROGRAMS APPROVED UNDER THIS SECTION;
18 (II) THE NUMBER OF STUDENTS WHO COMPLETED A
19 SHORT–TERM PROGRAM APPROVED UNDER THIS SECTION;
20 (III) IF THE INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION IS
21 NOT PHYSICALLY LOCATED IN THE STATE, THE NUMBER OF STATE RESIDENTS WHO:
22 1. ENROLLED IN THE SHORT–TERM PROGRAM; AND
23 2. COMPLETED THE SHORT–TERM PROGRAM;
24 (IV) THE TOTAL COST OF ATTENDANCE, THE TOTAL TUITION
25 AND FEES, AND THE AVERAGE NET PRICE OF THE SHORT–TERM PROGRAM; AND
26 (V) DEMOGRAPHIC AND FINANCIAL AID INFORMATION OF
27 STUDENTS ENROLLED IN THE SHORT–TERM PROGRAM.
28 (G) (1) (I) THE GOVERNOR’S WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT BOARD
29 SHALL REQUEST AND COLLECT RELEVANT DATA FROM EACH INSTITUTION OF
30 POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION OFFERING AN APPROVED SHORT–TERM PROGRAM.

8 SENATE BILL 509
1 (II) THE DATA COLLECTED UNDER SUBPARAGRAPH (I) OF THIS
2 PARAGRAPH MAY INCLUDE:
3 1. INFORMATION REGARDING EMPLOYER
4 PARTNERSHIPS;
5 2. JOB PLACEMENT SECTORS; AND
6 3. THE ALIGNMENT OF SHORT–TERM PROGRAM
7 CURRICULA WITH THE HIRING REQUIREMENTS OF IN–DEMAND INDUSTRY SECTORS.
8 (III) EACH INSTITUTION OF POSTSECONDARY EDUCATION
9 OFFERING AN APPROVED SHORT–TERM PROGRAM SHALL PROVIDE THE DATA
10 REQUESTED BY THE GOVERNOR’S WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT BOARD UNDER
11 THIS PARAGRAPH IN THE FORM AND MANNER REQUIRED BY THE BOARD.
12 (2) ON OR BEFORE SEPTEMBER 30 EACH YEAR, THE GOVERNOR’S
13 WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT BOARD AND THE COMMISSION SHALL REPORT TO THE
14 GENERAL ASSEMBLY, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT
15 ARTICLE, A SUMMARY OF THE REPORTS REQUIRED INFORMATION COLLECTED
16 UNDER PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION AND THE DEMOGRAPHIC AND
17 FINANCIAL AID INFORMATION OF STATE STUDENTS WHO ENROLLED IN
18 SHORT–TERM PROGRAMS APPROVED UNDER THIS SECTION.
19 (G) (H) THE GOVERNOR’S WORKFORCE DEVELOPMENT BOARD AND THE
20 COMMISSION MAY ADOPT REGULATIONS NECESSARY TO CARRY OUT THIS SECTION.
21 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect June
22 1, 2026.
Approved:
